Historical content entity objects are intentionally stripped of their space and linking page information to avoid coming up in a list of current pages, e.g. space.getPages().

This means you can't tell what space a page previously belonged to, or what parent a page previously had.

Perhaps lists of current pages should be aware that historical pages exist and not return them, so this information can be stored properly.

In a plugin, I have an action extending ConfluenceAction. Unfortunately bundles don't seem to be loaded automatically (which seems to impair my ability to use bundles into the templates associated with those actions).

To make things work, I have to include the following code:

    private final Map texts = new HashMap();
    public AutoExportAction() {
        /* Apparently bundle loading mechanism doesn't work in plugins */
        final String base = this.getClass().getName().replace('.','/');
        final ClassLoader loader = this.getClass().getClassLoader();
        final Locale locale = Locale.getDefault();
        ResourceBundle bundle = ResourceBundle.getBundle(base, locale, loader);
        Enumeration keys = bundle.getKeys();
        while (keys.hasMoreElements()) {
            final String key = (String) keys.nextElement();
            this.texts.put(key, bundle.getString(key));
        }
    }
    public String getText(String key) {
        final String result = (String) this.texts.get(key);
        if (result == null) return super.getText(key);
        return result;
    }

Basically load the bundle at construction of my plugin into a Map, and override "getText()" to first look in my local cache of the bundle...

