While writing my plugin, I noticed that a bug got introduced between 2.1 and 2.1.4: Example code:

public void handleEvent(ConfluenceEvent event) {
    if (event instanceof PageUpdateEvent) {
        Page page = ((PageEvent) event).getPage();
        AbstractPage orig = ((PageUpdateEvent) event).getOriginalPage();

        this.logger.debug("Page \"" + page.getTitle() + "\" in space \"" + page.getSpaceKey() + "\" updated");
        this.logger.debug("Original \"" + orig.getTitle() + "\" in space \"" + orig.getSpaceKey() + "\" updated");
    }
}

Both the orig.getSpaceKey() and the orig.getSpace() return null, which is kind of useful when listening on page events such as update or remove are intercepted (how do I know if a page was moved from one space to another?).

When loading a plugin I'm developing (uploading it through the web browser), the component specified in my "atlassian-plugin.xml" never gets loaded. Example:

<component name="Auto Export Manager"
                 class="it.could.confluence.autoexport.AutoExportManager"
                 key="autoExportManager" alias="autoExport">
    <description>A manager for all configuration aspects of the Auto Export plugin.</description>
</component> 

To have it properly initialize, I have to have this in the default constructor:

public AutoExportManager() {
    /* Hrmpf... It looks lik confluence doesn't autowire plugins */
    ContainerManager.autowireComponent(this);
}

This not only happens for <component/>s but also for <listener/>s and <action/>s.

